text: see what people are saying about candy apple butterscotch, #newauthor rebecca macceile’s debut publication. “this is an impactful read if you have ever experienced any sort of abuse. i appreciate the author’s candor and willingness to write with such openness. she takes responsibility for herself as much as she describes the lasting effects of trauma.” “it is worth the read. it’s about a woman empowered and, my god, that is a wonderful thing indeed.” “the author gets to the point while still painting a very clear and definite picture for the readers and i love that. the accounts of the trauma are laid out in such a way that you know what’s happening and are able to imagine it but you aren’t bombarded with intense graphic imagery, which i appreciate as a survivor myself. would definitely recommend!” “this amazingly written gem takes you inside the author’s world and keeps you there, making you feel like a discreet “bug on the wall.” i could not put it down.” “i wish everyone would write a memoir. it would be so much easier to understand people. i haven’t been through anything as violent or traumatic, but i think this story is relatable in a lot of ways. it just makes me see a lot of things differently in every day life. it’s a big eye opener.” #onsalenow at the #linkinbio. #kindle and #paperback versions available! also for members of #amazonprime, candy apple butterscotch is available in the #kindlelendinglibrary as well as through #kindleunlimitedbooks! that’s right you can read for #free. #nonfictionbooks #memoir #metoo #ptsdsurvivor #kindlestoryteller2018  #kindledirectpublishing #onsalenow #paperback #kindlelendinglibrary #bookrecommendations #indieauthor #authorsofinstagram #amazon #readforfreekll

text:
this is such an important article about the dangers of alcohol abuse and how challenging it is to treat. 
this quote was the most important part to me because it is so true. what other illness is left untreated these days?

we run around trying to avoid gluten and dairy and gmo but constantly laugh off the idea that alcohol is not safe, instead we lie to ourselves and believe the nonsense that it only hurts some people but it's safe for others. we would never smoke cigarettes in front of our children yet we drink around them and make jokes about it and exclude moms who don't drink. we would never tolerate it with any other drug, why is alcohol different?

it's time to end the stigma attached to alcoholics and substance abuse and change our behavior to be more accepting of someone's decision to say no thanks.

text:
#fstкорисніпоради
ключові тренди осені складні і самодостатні. їх можна носити як самостійно, так і змішувати між собою в будь-яких пропорціях. головне – мода цього сезону поважає небанальні поєднання і змінені пропорції тіла. vogue.ua вибрав 10 модних тенденцій, без яких буде важко скласти гардероб сезону осінь-зима 2018/19.

анімалістичний принт
цієї осені нікуди не сховатися від великої кількості анімалістичних принтів. мальовничі плями шкур леопарда, оцелота, зебри і тигра густо покрили подіуми чотирьох головних модних столиць світу. особливо ефектний вигляд матимуть нетрадиційні колірні поєднання "хижих" забарвлень з рожевим, малиновим або червоним.

логотипи
розпочата кілька сезонів тому лихоманка під назвою "логоманія" в новому сезоні зменшувати обертів не планує. не залишилися до неї байдужі цієї осені навіть такі стійкі до масових тенденцій бренди як max mara і prada.

кейпи
loewe, saint laurent, isabel marant і missoni знають толк в правильному верхньому одязі на осінь. вузькі пальта і піджаки, немов зняті з чоловічого плеча, змінюють просторі і розкішні кейпи. знову одяг супергероїв, оперних співаків і ченців-капуцинів справно слугуватиме на модній службі.

багатошаровість
багатошаровість не можна назвати чистим трендом цієї осені. як тільки стає холодно, природно, що вбрання починають сповзатися в один великий текстильний "пиріг". головна відмінність цього сезону – "найсмачніші" поєднання фактур. нейлон з хутром або шерстю, оксамитом чи шкірою.

сукня зі шкіри
шкіряні вбрання в епоху #metoo схожі на справжні модні лати і уніформу розгніваних домінатрікс. на поясі чи ні, довгі або мінімально короткі, похмуро чорні або життєрадісно помаранчеві – без них модний пазл цієї осені не складеться.

срібло
вбрання в монолуках під кодовою назвою all in silver зроблять їх володарку схожою на стрімку срібну кулю, на дівчину з футуристичних 1960-х або на головну діву танцполу з вісімдесятих.

плісирування
дрібне і ніжне плісирування на сукнях і спідницях затремтіло першим вересневим холодком. плісирування – найлегший і витончений тренд сезону.⬇️⬇️⬇️продовження в коментарях ⬇️⬇️⬇️

розпочата кілька сезонів тому лихоманка під назвою "логоманія" в новому сезоні зменшувати обертів не планує. не залишилися до неї байдужі цієї осені навіть такі стійкі до масових тенденцій бренди як max mara і prada.

кейпи
loewe, saint laurent, isabel marant і missoni знають толк в правильному верхньому одязі на осінь. вузькі пальта і піджаки, немов зняті з чоловічого плеча, змінюють просторі і розкішні кейпи. знову одяг супергероїв, оперних співаків і ченців-капуцинів справно слугуватиме на модній службі.

багатошаровість
багатошаровість не можна назвати чистим трендом цієї осені. як тільки стає холодно, природно, що вбрання починають сповзатися в один великий текстильний "пиріг". головна відмінність цього сезону – "найсмачніші" поєднання фактур. нейлон з хутром або шерстю, оксамитом чи шкірою.

сукня зі шкіри
шкіряні вбрання в епоху  схожі на справжні модні лати і уніформу розгніваних домінатрікс. на поясі чи ні, довгі або мінімально короткі, похмуро чорні або життєрадісно помаранчеві – без них модний пазл цієї осені не складеться.

срібло
вбрання в монолуках під кодовою назвою all in silver зроблять їх володарку схожою на стрімку срібну кулю, на дівчину з футуристичних 1960-х або на головну діву танцполу з вісімдесятих.

плісирування
дрібне і ніжне плісирування на сукнях і спідницях затремтіло першим вересневим холодком. плісирування – найлегший і витончений тренд сезону.⬇️⬇️⬇️продовження в коментарях ⬇️⬇️⬇️

text:
20180224
약자들의 정치 혐오는 기득권들에게는 무조건 이득이다. 약자들의 연대와 정치는 그들에게 게임체인저와 같은 두려움이니까. 이대 학생들의 영리하고 세련된 정치가 어떻게 이 나라를 흔들었는지 기억하지 못하는 국민은 거의 없다. 그래서 나는 그들이 정치 혐오를 계획적으로 조장한다는 확신에 가까운 의심을 가지고 있다. 초원복집 사건으로 그 실체는 조금이나마  드러났었다.

미투 운동은 정치적인게 맞다. 정치적이여야 한다. 이 운동과 대척점에 서 있는 기득권은 진보 보수를 가리지 않는 사회 전체이다. 적어도 수백년, 어쩌면 수천년동안 견고히 다져진 권력구도를 부수려는데 정치 말고 도대체 무슨 방법이 있을까? 그냥 적당히 문제 없을만큼만 저항하는 약자의 위치를 언제까지나 지켜달라는 소리로 밖에 들리지 않는다.

똥같은 정치를 하는놈들을 뚜까팰 수 있는 도구 역시 정치이다. 혐오하지 말고 손에 들고 휘두르자.

그리고 이 물결이 문화계에 그치지 않고 전 사회를 뒤엎기를 간절히 기원합니다.

#미투 #미투운동 #metoo #withyou #여성운동 #미소지니 #페미니즘 #정치 #정치혐오
name: 한남최범주

text:
i don’t have the time or energy to explain why what happened was so disgustingly wrong. why? because i should not have to explain basic decency, basic morality and empathy!! this poor girl humiliatingly had her underwear held up to the court room as some form of “proof” that she was asking for it. how absolutely humiliating for an already traumatised child. i once read “women are raped twice, once by the perpetrator, and again by the court”. abso-bloody-lutely! however... to see the absolute wonderful women protest against this horrendous act really brought a smile to my face. i love that the victim had so much support, and that we aren’t afraid to stand up and tell the world when something isn’t right. 
we will not be silenced!!! #sexualabuse #sexualassaultsurvivor #metoo #ibelieveher #ireland

text:
my daughter’s oh hell no face. 🌈
my daughter has this one face she makes, i call it her, "oh hell no," face. she raises her eyebrows and stares you down like, what the f is this?"
💥

she does it if she's had enough of someone taking pictures of her, or if we offer her a cherry when she wants a muffin.
🤮
her no is so clear. her anger, so unfettered.
🐅
she's only 2 now, so things will likely become more complicated for her.
🐾
i'm learning how to find my own, "oh hell no" face. learning to let my own anger be uncomplicated. it's big work.
☄️
i want to protect her no. i want to protect her anger. i want to protect her clarity about what she wants and what she most certainly does not want. i will fight for her however i can.
🖤
we took a hit, sisters. i'm not over it. not at all.
🚫
i know we're not surprised anymore. injustice always sucks and today it feels_really_personal. and i'm not sure what to do in this moment other than vote, donate, support causes i believe in, love my family, etc.
🔻
but i'm not skipping my anger. not today, patriarchy. not today.
🔻🔻🔻
#metoo #writersofinstagram #recovering #momsofinstagram #consentissexy #women #womenempowerment #womenwhowrite #writing #smashthepatriarchy #durga #kali #scorpioseason

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
#beyoncé parted ways with #topshop after allegations of racism and sexual harassment by owner #sirphillipgreen surfaced late last year. her company #parkwood has officially acquired all shares of her athleisure brand #ivypark from green’s #arcadiagroup . 🙌🏾 #metoo #fenomlife3 source [vogue]
********************************
“from the moment that allegations of racism and sexual harassment by topshop owner sir philip green arose in october, speculation around green’s involvement in beyoncé’s ivy park line began to percolate. since its launch in 2016, the popular athleisure label has been a fifty-fifty partnership between beyoncé’s company, parkwood, and green’s arcadia group—but the star put an end to that today, with her company announcing that it has bought out the british businessman’s shares, effectively ending their professional relationship. in a statement released to the financial times this afternoon, it was made clear that after yearlong discussions, the ivy park brand had been fully acquired by parkwood.” continue reading @ [vogue]

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that’s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him “we can take it.” no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it’s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

that’s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it’s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it’s that we’ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text: life update! i feel so good. like the weight of the world has been lifted from my shoulders. i told that intern that was harassing me to stop because it made me feel uncomfortable. he said that he was sorry and wouldn’t do it again. for the next few days, my boyfriend (who, yes, i know you all want to know who he is/what he looks like. that will happen soon - but love isn't the center of life, happiness is, so i’m focusing on that) would come into my building with either lunch or a flower or just to say hi. he didn’t like the idea of a fellow intern saying things like that to me, and i refused to let him address it himself, but we settled on little check-ins to make it known that i was taken and that my boyfriend is a very strong man lol. anyways, a few days later he decided to address me as a sexual object. he told a fellow intern (who sits right next to me - so yes he was right next to me) that he would gladly “park his car in my garage” while i bent down to grab the pen that i dropped. i looked right at him and told him that not only was that statement a terrible joke, but it qualified as sexual harassment and that i was going to report him to our boss and he could very well lose his position. he pleaded that he didn’t mean to say it out loud, but he would have still been thinking it. so i did just that. today i told my boss what was going on. they had me file a report and then they called him in (while i was still there) and fired him! us girls should never have to deal with anything like this. i let it go on for too long, it made my life miserable while i was at my internship. but he will no longer torment me or any other woman. us women have a voice now. let’s use it and scream at the top of our lungs for what we think is right. #metoo #mystory #sexualharassmentisneverokay

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

all praises to a #wndrwmn herself @_msestevez for providing a platform to celebrate and acknowledge black latinx icons!! •••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••• from @_msestevez :

so many of your faves benefit from black music, often without paying dues or homage. ‘footprints’ is #tidal’s latest video program, a fully animated series dedicated to celebrating the african and/or indigenous legacies inherent to the many forms of latinx song, dance and rhythm. given our climate and collective awakening, our premiere episode concerns specifically black latino icons (with exception of particular songs and genres) and their musical contributions to the culture, which indisputably paved the way for many of today’s superstars. big big thanks to @amaralanegraaln for agreeing to do voiceover narration; to @bousiko, whose beautiful art work made this idea possible — thank you a milli for signing on and bringing this to fruition. to @jesustalks for encouraging and assisting me, and for @tidal supporting this very necessary dialogue. 
link in her bio!!

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: “the pain stopped, and i immediately rolled over onto my side. i curled my knees tightly to my chest and continued to sob. i was unable to process what had just happened. instead of running away or calling for help, the only thing i could do was freeze and sob. i had no idea where noah had gone. i only knew that he was no longer hurting me. when i realized that he could still be in bed with me, i quickly stifled my sobs, which was more difficult than i’d anticipated. eventually, though, the tears stopped, exhaustion took over and i fell into a fitful sleep.” -r. macceile 2018 candy apple butterscotch: a memoir available now! #fourstars #memoir #metoo #ptsdsurvivor “it’s worth the read it’s about a #woman #empowered and my god that is a #wonderful thing indeed” #linkinbio #authorsofinstagram #independentpublishing #goodreads #newbookalert #readforfree

text:
i wanted to give up so many times in my life. 
when life hits you hard, you feel like you're backed into a corner...suffocating...drowning in quicksand..waiting for someone to pull you out. waiting for life to get even just a little bit better.

you are faced with two options:
give up or put up one heck of a fight.

i have learned that the more you keep fighting through whatever it is you are dealing with, the stronger it is you become. i speak from experience, not just some cliche talking.

life is tough. right??? but if we give up now before life gets better again..we won't see the fruit of our works. our strength..our triumph! 
if you feel like giving up, hang in there. i know it may seem like a far fetched, unimaginable idea that life can get better, but it can. just hang in there. please...don't give up.

you are needed in this world. everything you encompass is extraordinary. it's unique. whether you believe the words i am typing or not. it's true.

i love you so much. just hang in there. fight. give it everything you got and a little more. i know you can do this.

don't give up on me..
never give up.

#youmatter
#iamthefaceof

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

the 5th oil that comes in your starter kit is peppermint! peppermint is not just good for the holidays but all times of the year! it is great for energy support and all things tension related! 
my absolute fave way to use peppermint is along with lemon and lavender in my seasonal support roller! i roll it on my temples and back of neck for relief from the pesky season change and because cats are not my friends🐈 🙅🏼.
i mentioned that peppermint with digize is a dynamic duo for tummy troubles in my previous post. i’m going to mention it again because it’s just that good! 🙌🏼 put these 2 in a roller and roll on your stomach in a clockwise motion and start your happy dance! 💃🏻 if riding in the car makes you feel uneasy this oil will be your bestie! either keep a bottle in the car to huff or put some on cotton balls and stick it in you air vent! 
feeling festive? add a drop or 2 to your hot cocoa, tea, or coffee!

text:
richard branson quotes bore us and people and businesses that re-quote him bore and offend us. he's just another self-entitled rich white guy with nothing that speaks to us.
in 1971, branson was convicted and briefly jailed for tax evasion, having fraudulently obtained export documents for records to be sold on the domestic market. branson was advised of the sting by an anonymous tip-off and attempted to dispose of the evidence, but this was unsuccessful.
branson's business empire is owned by a complicated series of offshore trusts and companies. the sunday times stated that his wealth is calculated at £3 billion; if he were to retire to his caribbean island and liquidate all ofthis, he would pay relatively little in tax. branson has been criticised for his business strategy, and has been accused of being a carpetbagger. branson responded that he is living on necker for health rather than tax reasons.
in 2013, branson described himself as a "tax exile", having saved millions in tax by surrendering his british citizenship. this was echoed by  labour's john mcdonnell in 2016, amid calls for his knighthood to be revoked.

promotion of seaworld

branson has been criticised by the whale and dolphin conservation organisation for profiting from selling trips to seaworld and similar themed parks that hold dolphins, whales and other sea life in captivity for entertainment purposes.

assault claim

text:
《就算有點敏感也沒關係 좀 예민해도 괜찮아!》(共12集)
推薦指數：🌕🌕🌕🌕🌕(滿分!)
網介：該劇講述二十歲的年輕人在校園內經歷的性別上的困擾，劇情將圍繞著性差別待,性別不公等問題展開
🐷：這部不只是單純的校園甜劇 還把社會上存在的各種議題很真實的呈現出來了 結尾都會留上一句鼓勵人的話 提醒女性們要多留意身邊 發生事情的時候也要勇敢的站出來

text:
nominated for a 23rd red nation international film festival best short subject documentary award, our rematriation magazine film “an indigenous response to #metoo” is a new half-hour film featuring a group of cultural change-makers from haudenosaunee six nations territories and the guachichil de la gran chichimeca. the film’s purpose is to share a culturally grounded and relevant response to address the #metoo movement in indigenous communities, to start group conversations and to lean into culturally based solutions. to book screenings with discussions in your community, contact us at together@rematriation.com or (315) 925-7191.

text: this is huge. i can't believe i'm actually saying it. the second project i wrote and directed has been selected for my local film festival! tally shorts is an awesome fest in tallahassee, florida that exclusively showcases awesome shorts made locally and internationally. i've been working and working and learning what it means to be a serious filmmaker for the past 7 years and this is an amazing opportunity to prove that all that work is paying off. i'm so privileged and excited to be able to share my story and give a voice to a problem that millions and millions of people face all the time. thank you to my awesome, talented, and good-looking cinematographer, brett allbritton. you bring so much to my life and i love the art we make together!! #film #filmmaker #florida #floridafilmmaker #womandirector #metoo #tallyshorts #tallyshortsfilmfestival #writtenanddirectedbyme

text:
i needed a minute!!
*
after escaping my 5-year nightmare posing as a committed relationship, i needed some down time. the next six months of my life would be completely dedicated to figuring out why i kept committing myself to 💩💩 relationships.
*
well, i took the six months but it took almost another six years to realize my brokenness attracted brokenness. and i committed to it because it was so familiar to me. in order to find something whole, i had to become whole again.
*
your potential lies in those shattered pieces. the people that broke your spirit and betrayed your trust are depending on you to stay broken. the enemy knows that once you heal and become whole again, there’s no stopping you!
*
put those broken pieces back together are start attracting the real allies you deserve. •

i posted in a local community forum for freelance work dog sitting, cleaning, and babysitting. 
i am about up to here with this bullshit. this uninvited sexual harrasment , simply because i am attractive i am perceived to "want it" , or "ask for these advances" it's enoughhhhhhh! i usually brush this off because it happens so often but this idiot put his full name so i'm putting it out there. women are afraid to put themselves out their and be independent because of shit like this. there are plenty of platforms available for that type of service , and hunny i am not the one. my post being clear, concise, and professional outlining my professional experiences with an appropriate head shot from the neck up ! like really asshole , come on please check yourself and make this world a safer space for women, and here's a fucking thought, #respect ,she doesn't ask for it , hunny it means she doesnt want it! women are not going to back down and brush this shit off any more so good luck ryan anderson . oh and that goes for couples too , sooo beyond over couples harrasing a lesbian to sleep with you two #thirsty asses, like again find like minded people for this!

text:
the theater at the 14th street y announces 2018-2019 season lgbtq+ series

the theater at the 14th street y continues tohonor the edgy, diverse, and rich history of innovative culture making in the east village for people of all ages with the 2018-2019 lgbtq+ series.the series kicked off on november 12, 2018 with #nastywomen, a night of female resistance comedy and runs through april 2019."for our season of war & peace, we knew that artists from the lgbtq community would have a strong reaction to the theme. coming out can often feel like war and creating a family can bring much needed peace. our lgbtq offerings this season have addressed the gamut, from vietnam veterans coming to terms with their sexuality to a tya show with a non-gender binary protagonist to a piece about a modern family facing discrimination from within. our theater is a safe place for provocative work that will inspire conversation, debate and hopefully action," said ronit muszkatblit, artistic director.different translation november 29 - december 16, 2018 written by david stallings, directed by antonio miniño when claire's concerns over the welfare of her two-year old cousin are dangerously validated, she begins to question the family's principals and ability to parent. a crucial new play, exploring same-sex parenting and cis family values in today's america. after the december 7 performance, guests will be invited to an lgbtq mixer with free drinks and appetizers with the cast and crew. a night of female resistance comedy
comedyistheresistance.com
january 28, april 15, may 20, 2019
curated by laura beatrix newmark
following the women's march and in light of the #metoo, time's up, #neveragain movements, we provide a forum for female comedians that empowers all through laughter, camaraderie and tangible activism tools. nasty women's second season includes a show in april celebrating her, they and us, from comedians of transgender experience. #commentsplease #explorepage😍 #lgbtqtravelers #pleasecomments #200likes #lgbtqiapd #comments😻 #followers #comments🎵💗 #10likes #jualfollowers #lgbtq🌈 #autocomments #100likes #20likes #lgbtqcommunity #explorepage❤️ #ilovemyfollowers #explorepage✨

text:
feeling really good to announce this upcoming workshop i am facilitating at stretch vancouver on december 16, from 7-9pm.  tickets at eventbrite, link in my bio. 
this #metoo beathwork event is the first of its kind, and has been carefully made for the healing of anyone who has been subjected to sexual abuse of any kind. 
in this two hour workshop, we will connect with other people who have also experienced sexual abuse, harassment, rape, or assault, and give each other a chance to be heard and release anything that's ready to come out.
we will also be doing one hour of clarity breathwork, which is a continuous breathing technique that floods the body with oxygen and helps to reset the nervous system. it also can allow traumas to be released from the body, and provide great clarity on how we truly feel inside. that gives way to a deeper connection with self, and the body which is often dissociated after abuse.

this is a place to heal, and let go, without fear of judgement. we will create a supportive container together, in the hopes that each of us can leave feeling a bit lighter, and a bit more connected to both the self and the greater community because this is an issue that has impacted so many of us.

come to try it out, come to connect, come to heal.

i look forward to seeing you there, this is an issue that is near and dear to my heart. it is my wish to help create a safe space beyond the hashtags, where we can come together in community to heal and move forward.

please ask any questions you may have, see you then. -asta

text:
may we heal from this #fire. may we find our path to global #healing. may our missing aunties, neighbors, and friends be found #alive. if not, may we as their grieving survivors claim our #voice and #money from those entities who created the disaster if it wasn’t of natural, earthly origins. 
#reparations means repairing the damage that can be fixed and using community #knowledge to prevent future losses of the same #kind. below are some ideas about how to calculate for financial reparations. this is a work in progress. under conditions of intense vulnerability, i practice “quick release” aka “#rapidprototyping. 
first, there is no one method or formula for determining reparations.

so much of the violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this earth #walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo.

second, calculating reparations is always an #economic and #spiritual practice.

above all, the spiritual dimension of this method is central, and #survivors must lead each #initiative. the point is to foster healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the support we require to create solutions for ourselves and our #beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to learn and apply the method?

from a purely economic perspective, what aspects of healing can financial reparations facilitate? this question is the most direct, but it isn't as simple as it sounds. for example, you might desire therapy and know that therapists cost a rate of, say $60-250 an hour in your town. what if no therapist in your local beloved community speaks your mother language of #quechua or #spanish or #tagalog and that's the language in which you sense the world? what is the honest price tag for your therapy sessions if you have to travel three hours to see a therapist who shares your cultural, linguistic, ancestral #perspective?

you can read the rest by searching my page 💚🕊

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
for the last two years, i've been working on a project to decolonize social enterprise and help folks work together to regenerate our global ecosystem and practice beloved community. you can read more about that in other posts to this blog or do a search for #decolonialbiznessworld on this platform or elsewhere if you're curious.

the focus of this post is the lessons i've learned from linkedin.

i didn't plan to create a method of business education aimed at reparations and decolonization. it just happened. decolonial bizness world came to me post-hack.

you see, for the last four years i've been the target of hackers, some known and others not. you can find posts on being hacked in the archive of writings you see here, on linkedin, if you search my writing. i won't include links directly because, well, that's not the focus. this tidbit is for context.

two years ago, after many hacks of small and large impact, i lost everything in what i've come to call a "full stack hack." in the world of engineering, a full stack developer is someone who handles all aspects of digital systems, from databases to servers and clients to apps. i use the term full stack hack to speak to my life after i lost access to:

1️⃣the digital archives that stored my papers such as half a completed book manuscript, syllabi, and notes from more than a decade;
2️⃣my personal and academic email accounts; and
3️⃣my phone.
no joke. my phone got #smoky and was #toast in mere minutes. the #smoke effect was a sight to behold. it started in the bottom right corner and kept going and growing until #goodbye smartphone.

all this happened within a week or so. i don't recall the details or exact timeline; i was terrified and the consequences were swift and long-lasting. posts from that time also appear in this archive, as this platform was one of the few i was able to access during that full stack hack of my life/work.

since that time, i've used this blog to share drafts and more polished work. i've made edits and even complete deletions to what you can view -- and #metoo. the digital imprint remains in the cloud.

as this #fullstack #hack was happening in late 2016, i started to #migrate content....

text:
in 2014, steve bannon – then executive chairman of the “alt-right” news network breitbart – was christopher wylie’s boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica’s investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology – “information operations” – then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica’s parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it’s insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it’s like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in "broke," #lecrae testifies to how poverty can make people #wealthy. isn't that a #beautiful teaching? and how #sweet to see a leader who makes sense!

we need our #prophets of truth to displace the lie of profit.

this idea is central to the teachings of #decolonialbiznessworld. in decolonial bizness world, there's the #soil of natural #abundance at the base of the #treeoflife, which starts at the heart with #selflove and includes #belovedcommunity and true love for #mothernature, who's now on strike.

you see, when i'm not pushed into the position of having to call out tech companies like #google, #facebook, and #linkedin for protecting #predators, i'm drawing upon community knowledge to help people #decolonize business #leadership so that we can transform a world system that creates financial poverty and profits from it.

as if that is the only form of violence at play in the world today. #4645boricuas.

in the case of #facebook, for example, a sexual predator or collection of them used my full legal name, darshan elena campos, to sell porn and sex via facebook for at least two months. i'll spare you all the details but this truth: facebook refused to remove the page. one day, it just disappeared. #poof.

i have been locked out of posting images and videos to instagram since 4 july 2018 when i organized a free event, which asked what freedom means to #nativepeoples, slaves, colonial subjects, and babies locked in a cage. i can't delete what's pending, and i can't log out either.

i am trapped.

i want to review the data trail. and, i want that personal and corporate information to be released to the #digitalcommons so that we can figure out how to better #respond to digitized sexual violence.

as for me, i also want to see the numbers in #dollars and #data so that i can design curriculum for decolonial bizness world on how ambitious social justice warriors such as myself can combat today's market failure of people trapped in similar situations. #metoo. i've been a victim, and i refuse to remain in the shadows. #timesup. i am not alone. #niunamenos.

1/2 cup frozen tropical fruit mix
1/2 banana
1 cup water
5 ice cubes
*
i kept this simple. it was a nice treat after the rather eventful day i had. i think it even kept me from eating some white fudge oreos today 😁
*
today in walmart i had a very unapologetically me moment. i didn’t even realize i’d done it until the lady giving me the unsolicited advice seemed offended. i didn’t even know what her advice was because i’m not a huge fan of unsolicited advice. i wasn’t even listening.
*
normally i would have listened and in some way acknowledged the receipt of said wisdom.  gotta please the people ya know. this time i just didn’t give a 💩. it is a very liberating feeling - finding my way and being more comfortable with the process. 
day 320 is in the books...❤️❤️

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

tweet_full:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
trigger warning, a panic attack #share on being the target of hackers, at least one of whom is a known sexual predator and a google engineer.

today i need to go to the apple store. i need to buy the right cable for the laptop i have so that it can plug into the community energy grid at the #farm where i spend a lot of time. the farm runs on living #energy, not fossil energy like oil and gas, so i need a new set of cords.

i'm going there, to the farm, since i'm less #safe in my home community than on the road or migratory. i'm also going to the farm because i'm #boricua (google #4645boricuas) and invested in climate #solutions. there, i'm designing starter kits for #freeglobaldistribution of the farm's community energy grid. i'm not an engineer or a tech writer, but i'm #smart, handy, and pretty #resilient in the face of personal and political disaster.

although resilient, i'm panicky at the moment because it isn't just a new cable. my entire digital system of devices is being pesky, and i need to look at that too. and that's the point of this post: #digital (in)#security for colored girls who want to live when we're a moving target.

truth: my iphone only #rings when it wants to. the texts never #beep. even people who use iphones don't understand my smartphone. my phone's challenges stumped a #13 year old who has an apple phone, which says a lot.

so you see, i'm panicky because it isn't just a trip to the store in #preparation for farm life below the mason-dixon line. it is a trip down trauma lane, which makes no sense and goes round and round, before i leave the house in st. louis where i've been for the last week. for the last two months i've been here, in st. louis, and this is the fourth home i've stayed in.

you confused yet? #metoo. let's do some trauma mapping together. i'll just tell the tale as it wants to be told.

apple is the company that employs one of my oldest, closest friends who doesn't speak to me anymore. when i was first trapped in this desperate situation -- you know, the one that involved me learning in 2014 that my love for seven plus years, a google engineer, was a sexual predator, a "discovery" which trapped me in two court cases....
name: darshan elena campos

text:
словарь collins назвал слово года
⠀
составители толкового словаря английского языка collins выбрали словом 2018 года «одноразовый» («single-use») — это слово описывает предметы, сделанные из пластика, неконтролируемое использование которого наносит ущерб окружающей среде.
⠀
за период с 2013 года употребление этого слова увеличилось в четыре раза. особенно часто упоминаемым оно стало после запрета на территории ес одноразового пластика в октябре 2018 года.
⠀
в шортлист в этом году также попали слова #metoo (хештег, призывающих к борьбе с харассментом), gaslight (намеренное убеждение человека в ложности его мыслей) и whitewash (использование белых актёров на роли темнокожих).
⠀
⠀
collins dictionary named word of year
⠀
the authors of the collins english dictionary have chosen the word «single-use» as the word of 2018. the word describes objects made of plastic. using them unconsciously, we do harm to the environment.
⠀
since 2013 the word has become four times more popular. its usage especially increased after the eu ban on plastic in 2018.
⠀
among the words on the short list were also #metoo (anti-harassment hashtag), gaslight (deliberately convincing someone that their thoughts are false) and whitewash (using white actors to play black people).
name: SPIBA

text:
my soon to be work space, again. 
sometimes you just have to start over. life happens and things get messy. it means you’re living!! today has been full of little projects. nikki made a space on her side for a makeup table. i went and bought a 3-way pvc piece to make her a holder for her hairdryer and straightener. 
there’s little signs of progress all over the house. little signs of improvements that have been days, weeks, or even months in the making. 
it shows all the other work that doesn’t get seen has begun to pay off. we don’t always get to see progress overnight. there’s no miracle pill, wrap, or drink that causes you to lose weight/fat that quickly (that is safe). you’ve got to put the work in. you gotta make it happen. this is the first night i’ve seen the desk in months but there were other things that were more important to get done first. doesn’t mean i ignored it; it means it wasn’t a priority. 
don’t waste your time stressing over the one thing that you couldn’t get to; stress over missing the big things that matter - like time with family and friends. tomorrow is not given. 
#workinprogress #jeremiah2911 #prayersandbarbells #trustandbelieve #metoo #bemyguest #pugmom

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

cnn

join us at the international human rights art festival @hrartfestival on sunday, november 18 at 4:00pm! the festival is an ongoing series of art-activist events, workshops, and community programs at the intersection of art, advocacy, and society.
.
a handful of us graduates of the emerging choreographer series will be creating live choreography in the class demonstration of @mnelements’ teaching method, the wave within, which has helped us develop our skills and original co-creative pieces for healing.
.
then enjoy the performance of altering, a dance work loosely inspired by the #metoo movement created by ecs 2018 choreographer patrick o’brien.
.
thanks and shout out to @mnelements! we are honored to partner with your great work and how it addresses human rights issues and artists’ responsibility to be conscious, proactive members of society. it’s going to be moving and lots of fun for everyone, too!
.
hurry and get tickets here! https://web.ovationtix.com/trs/pe.c/10332470
.
.
.

text: hey guys, i know i haven’t been as active as usual but i’ve had a lot going on in this past week. first, i’m a little homesick but am counting down the days until i get to see my family even though we currently have a lot of family drama going on in that moment. second, i found a guy i really like and he’s in one of my classes. we hung out a little and i started to really like him. yesterday a girl talked to me and told me that he acted the same way with her a couple weeks ago and they slept together and right after he stopped talking to her. she told me he does this with a lot of girls and that he and his friends have a competition to see who can have sex with the most girls their first semester. obviously the whole competition thing is really fucked up and i think i believe this girl even though i don’t know her well. nothing happened between him and i and now i know for sure i’m not gonna let anything happen. i just feel really upset right now, because girls aren’t objects and we aren’t just another notch in the bed. it makes me upset to think that this is all guys want and i just don’t know why i can’t find a nice guy who actually likes me and isn’t just trying to get into my pants... sorry for ranting i’m just really upset right now, i love you guys and thank you so much for your constant support ❤️-rissy  #love #youareenough #loveyourselffirst #quotes #quotesdaily #inspiration #sexualassault #empowerment  #survivor #metoo #metoomovement #recovery #feminist #feminism #feministquote  #trauma #female #inspirationalquote #equality #trigger #triggerwarning #assault #ptsd #mybodymychoice #consent #endrapeculture #timesup #depression #anxiety

text:
nigerian author chimamanda ngozi adichie was featured on the cover of the october 27 issue of telegraph magazine, where she discussed nigeria, misogyny, and the #metoo movement.

chimamanda talked about losing faith in nigeria after her father was kidnapped in 2015, how she feels he was kidnapped because of her.

she said:

it was because of me. that incident affected my father – it robbed him of something; there’s a distrust that he didn’t have before. he comes from a generation with a certain kind of integrity. for a long time he didn’t understand things like bribery – it just perplexed him. my father had given his everything – he got his phd in the us and he had job offers there in the 1960s, but he was keen to come back to nigeria.

nigerian author chimamanda ngozi adichie was featured on the cover of the october 27 issue of telegraph magazine, where she discussed nigeria, misogyny, and the #metoo movement.

chimamanda talked about losing faith in nigeria after her father was kidnapped in 2015, how she feels he was kidnapped because of her.

she said:

it was because of me. that incident affected my father – it robbed him of something; there’s a distrust that he didn’t have before. he comes from a generation with a certain kind of integrity. for a long time he didn’t understand things like bribery – it just perplexed him. my father had given his everything – he got his phd in the us and he had job offers there in the 1960s, but he was keen to come back to nigeria.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
a few days ago someone close to me was walking home alone  around 8 pm when a piece of shit of a man grabbed her and was able to immobilize her while her screems got the attention of a neighbors dog and the neighbor was able to save her from what it would have been a violent rape right here in mairena, in what is one of the lowest crime areas in all of seville. 
the perpetuator, 16-20 year old, tall, dark hair, totally normal looking guy ran away and was not found.
the idea of this happening to anyone close to me horrifies me and fills me with tears, the idea that this happens every minute to a girl around the world makes me sick.

my inner circle is curated with pretty amazing people, both man and women uncapable of such thing, so i never ask myself questions like:
what was in his fucking mind? what gives him right?
what can we do to stop this from happening? what makes a man do something like this?  who is rasing this kind of monsters? what can i do???? why don't we talk about this kind of thing when it happens? why does it bring shame to the victim? so on and so on... and i come back to around a year ago to a wedding, when an a acquaintance , slid his fingers on back, saying total  inappropriate sexual comments...etc... i left the party and removed myself from the enviroment instead of confronting the man helping normalize this kind of shit. yeah, and i could go on with stories like that from the past some what similar to the last and see a clear pattern: some ashole says something stupid, i get away, don't talk about it and even make excuses (he just doesn't have commun sense. he had just too much to drink. he is annoying but he doesn't mean it like that, i propably said something to encourrage him) are we active part of the problem?
we should be able to walk home alone, or go to a party, or dress how ever the fuck we want with out being hassared or even rape. but reality indicates other wise. 
we need to protect ourselves, talk about when it happens and confront when we are being harrased. is not ok to not feel safe. 
my heart goes out to all of you girls who had been in similar situation. i'm sorry the world is so fucked up. #metoo

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
today i felt so lucky.
so lucky to live in a place where i am free to say as i please. 
so lucky to have all these women, united, supporting one another, fighting something as big as this, as global as this. 
so lucky to be able to say we’re sick of the rape, sexual abuse, verbal abuse, degrading slurs, violence, discrimination, sexism, slut shaming, victim blaming crap. 
we have a voice. today it was louder than ever, roaring through the city. 
so lucky to have met such amazing people and heard their stories, heard their voices. 
this makes me feel so whole. so at peace. so in awe of these people. 
i’m just hoping maybe change can happen someday so we can come together for a reason that doesn’t cause such pain.
thankyou thankyou thankyou to everyone who came along, joined in along the way it came for support it was such a good turnout ✨😭 i’m feeling so empowered and stronger than ever emotionally and spiritually ❤️❤️ #slutwalkmelbourne2018 
#slutwalk #slutwalkmelbourne #endvictimblaming #everyoneisaslut 
#stopslutshaming #stopthestigma #abolishrapeculture #stillnotaskingforit #metoo #metoomovement

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text: my first clay sculpture in college, and first time with polymer clay. the concept was really important to me, so i went all out with meticulous planning, anatomical research, measuring and countless hours. it became truly a form of art therapy. however once i fired it i fell into a bit of a slump internally, as i had been focusing so much energy on this piece. i realize now that it is a testament to resilience and self compassion in ways i never intended. it is finally sculpted and fired, however still some perfectionist fine tuning... artist statement to come once the piece is completely finished in mid december... #polymerclay #nudesculpture #compassion #universalcompassion #metoo #anatomystudy

text: • kingsley amis was brilliant at portraying otherwise ordinary characters in an incisively funny way, and this novel was no exception. there's jenny, the 'chaste' & very pretty young teacher, away from home for the first time and having to fend off the lascivious advances of her boyfriend patrick, and her creepy landlord dick thompson. the novel recounts jenny's experience entering the world of work in 1960 britain and the dynamics of dealing with a boyfriend with only one aim in mind. up to a point patrick was a sort of likeable cad, i mean lad, and then his conduct at a drunken party put him squarely in the criminal category and would at the very least have made him a candidate for the #metoo movement if it had existed in 1960, which it did not, clearly. so there are interesting issues of consent here, in a book very much of its era, but read against a 2018 backdrop. i would like to think that even in 1960 this character's conduct was received with censure, but i'm not sure it was. sigh ... •

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: i dag skal @arbeiderpartiet velge representanter til nye ålesund; det skjer på #gomerhuset i #skodje. de fleste såkalte ‘frivillige’ i #fjordcadenza også #grunder; #konkursrytter  #jensmoe fra skodje som bor i #usa #fortlauderdale sympatiserer med #arbeiderpartiet - som allerede har hatt sine saker i #metoo ..#trondgiske måtte forlate sine verv på grunn av overgrep mot kvinner - men det at giske klappes inn igjen viser mangelen på respekt i #arbeiderpartiet for kvinner generelt og for overgrepsutsatte kvinner spesielt. på valg i dag står blant annet #geiroveleite; #varaordfører i skodje; hans kone (ansatt i #navålesund..) deltok aktivt 17.08.18 i trakassering og bære ut #aksjonsofaslitern og kneblet kvinnes #ytringsfrihet (min!) der jeg aksjonerte fredelig med forhåndsinnhentet polititillatelse. også #tovenygård såkalt ‘frivillig’ i fjordcadenza står på valg i dag. disse ‘bevisstløse’ kvinner i #arbeiderpartiet løper testosteronmenn sitt ærende ved å akseptere voldelig handling 17.08.18 fra grunder og konkursrytter #jensmoe mot meg; text:
the end not proven campaign was launched by myself and @rapecrisisscotland this week. with the huge help of @bbcnews @stv.news and the fabulous @fidjit and @pieute ❤️ .
the not proven verdict is used disproportionately in rape cases. 
in 2016/17, only 39% of rape and attempted rape cases resulted in convictions, the lowest rate for any type of crime. nearly 30% of acquittals were not proven, compared with 17% for all crimes and offences.

the not proven verdict has the exact same impact as a not guilty verdict, and can be just as distressing for the complainer as a not guilty verdict.

i am calling on the scottish government to give survivors a chance. there is no convincing argument to retain the outdated verdict, it’s time to scrap not proven for good.

image credit: @fidjit 
please share this information and spread the word about this important campaign.
