text:
i was recently put in this situation. no choice. i wish i was able to say the same as what is said in the picture, but i froze up, just like the first time. 
you might be like... but why are you even telling me this? because... we are shaped by many things. trauma is a big contributor to the way we are today, personality wise or even mental illnesses that took form. we need to learn to be more tolerant and patient with one another. you never know what people are going through. talk to your loved ones. be there for them. love them. show them that you love them for who they've become. we need to know that. 
i am not someone that share personal things, but i'm honored to have this anonymous platform, something which many in the same situation don't have. so i need to use it to just get people talking, thinking in critical ways as to how we can break the stigma. let me know if you want to work on something or just share a story. ⁣#mentalillness #mentalillnessmemes #mentalhealth #proud #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealthmatters #bipolarmemes #bipolar #bipolardisorder #bipolarsurvivor #bipolarawareness #bipolarquotes #suicidesurvivor #bipolar1 #bipolar2 #manic #depressed #hypomanic #yourenotalone #endthestigma #inthistogether #mentalhealth #loveyourself #youaregoodenough #sexualassault #metoo #believesurvivors #whyididntreport #timesup

text:
.
i know i'm not alone
when i feel confronted
when i ponder...
what does it mean
to be a woman in 2018?

today i sat with local women
under a big ass tree
many of whom
i've never met before
(where have i been?)
.
determined not to cry
(not yet! too soon!)
before a word was uttered
before anyone shared
their story...
.
i sat under that tree
with my kids
and felt our collective strength
our collective energy
our power.

and boy, we are strong
you wouldn't wanna
fuck with us
not any of us.

yet we will hear you
we will listen
there is no anger
just smiles
understanding
and nods.

i am feeling incredibly honoured to be a part of jsp's next event coming up in february 2019 and i can't wait to share more with you here soon xx

text:
part 1:
i was sexually assaulted when i was 16. i was with a (female) friend at that day, who had also invited another (male, 20-something at the time) friend of hers, i didn't know him before, but we got along great. i live about two to three hours from my friend when i take the bus, however, the guys parents don't live far from me, so he offered to drive me home in order to visit them afterwards. i gladly agreed, since that would take less than an hour, also i enjoyed talking to him. in the car, he asked me if i wanted to hang out a little more, since it wasn't even afternoon, i agreed. 
however, while we were driving it started to get uncomfortable. earlier the day, i already stated that i was gay (i don't remember why exactly we talked about it, but the point is, he knew) and he started to go on and on about how that was "such a pity", i'm "too pretty to be a lesbian" and how i was totally his type. i pretty much just chuckled nervously at everything he said, confirming i was gay and not at all interested over and over again, already not really wanting to hang out anymore, but also too shy to tell him that. he stopped the car at some field, a few minutes drive away from the next village (or any civilization at all, really) and we sat down in the backseat to talk. i thought that we just could get over the conversation about me being gay and just talk about something else, but nothing really felt right or comfortable anymore and i already couldn't wait for an excuse to get home. then, he kissed me. i was in shock and didn't react at all. he proceeded to touch my body, especially my boobs and butt, also sliding his hands between my legs, telling me how sexy i was. i didn't manage to do anything besides staring at him (and i still hate myself for that), only finally reacting as he put my hand on his crotch, i pulled it away. however, the next twenty minutes or so, he still continued to touch me, putting his hands under my shirt, kissing me, "complimenting" me and i still was too much in shock to really react. 
#metoo #sexualassault #depression #advice

text:
society is arranged in such a way  as "what is between your legs is determined more than just your gender". i've noticed that there are a lot of yoni, vagina and pussy campaigns popping up the last year. this probably also has to do with the #metoo movement. the third feminist wave seems to be a fact nowadays. i'm calling myself a (prosexual) feminist as well but i've noticed that this word is been used so often that it sometimes loses it's impact/strength. sometimes i'm asking myself why it's called feminism? does this mean that there are two types of women? and why ain't there two types of man? the men is socially presented as powerful and dominant. that brings me to the answer that i'm always giving when people ask me about how i look at feminism and how i see myself as a feminist. to me man and women are different. we do have different genitals which have their own characteristics. we do have different ways of experiencing. but don't we have that all? as we all have our own individual feelings, beliefs and experiences. to me being a feminist is to strive for the same chances. to me feminism is about self-recognition, appreciation and development. to me feminism is about being the women who i want to be. without forced into the shackles of the social women image. what about you?

we are currently waking up to the recent lacy underwear humiliation, but we must not forget the travelers, the women of colour, elderly, trans,  disability, children and men that do not report rape. we must rally for every victim.

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: 8 years ago, i was sexually harassed by a drunk middle-aged man at a beach in goa. i was 11. i still remember the man very vividly in my head, his face, his actions, him. the beach, to me, has always been a place of comfort, a place where i find peace. the ocean reflects my soul. it hides within itself the deepest secrets and thus i buried, my fear and my discomfort, within the depths of my heart. and today, i rise, today i rise from the past that held me back, the past i once burdened myself with. more power to every fighter out there. you’re strong, precious and absolutely beautiful. #metoo

svezia, oggi. ingrid stern, victoria brunberg e birgitta nilsson sono tre donne di età diverse, unite dalla disperazione e dall'odio verso i mariti, uomini abituati alla violenza, alla sopraffazione, all'abuso fisico e verbale. l'eco del #metoo fa da eco alle loro storie, così simili e solitarie, apparentemente destinate a restare nell'ombra. quando grazie alla rete le tre donne si conoscono, scoprono che una può essere la forza dell'altra, la sua via d'uscita, l'ultima speranza.
"donne che non perdonano" di camilla läckberg è una crime story senza detective. il grido liberatorio di chi non vuole più abbassare la voce.

text:
this evening @yogarootspetoskey ❤️✨ a safe, sacred space for survivors to gather in grace. this healing circle will explore self-care techniques to heal spiritual and emotional pain. learn how to use affirmations, mindfulness and breath work to cultivate acceptance and inner peace. our time together will include gentle yoga and a sound healing session. 
this is our second meeting, new-comers are welcome. at the first meeting we discussed our coping mechanisms. two suggestions made by group members, one a burn journal, and the second a love letter to one's self have become themes for our next meeting. inspired by these suggestions we will start with a fire, where you may burn any journaled pages you want to let go of, anything you don't want others to read. then we will circle up inside and read the love letters (optional), and continue our discussion on self-care and coping mechanisms. we will conclude our gathering with gentle/restorative yoga and end with sound healing. 
this event is donation based, proceeds will benefit the women's resource center. door will be locked at the start of event, please arrive early. studio entrance is through the back door off the alley.

tiffany lenau, founder of yoga roots, it a sexual assault survivor of 20+ years. after healing her own wounds she is ready to share her coping skills with others and is honored to hold space for others on their path to healing. 
#newday
#metoo
#timesup

text:
god is alpha & omega, but he is also medio! 
god can, at anytime, clear up the mess. one may ask, but when i was in the middle of that mess where was god? in the middle god was silent. in the middle i was alone. 
in the middle, in the furnace of affliction, we are refined. 
the middle is where we learn how to utterly rely on him.  the middle is where made to examine ourselves & our motives. the middle is where shedding takes place. a shedding that refines us and draws us closer to him.

so wait for his timing and learn all he wants you to learn in your middle moments.

romans 8:28 assures us that "god causes all things to work together for good to those who love him, to those who are called according to his purpose." but the next verse tells us how god works all things for good in our lives: "for those whom he foreknew, he also predestined to become conformed to the image of his son...." there it is. god wants us to become more like his son through our struggles. so be teachable. be open to what he wants you to learn. and be moldable. you - and your heart - might be the one reason god has not yet fixed the situation.

text:
jede vierte frau wurde in deutschland, laut statistiken, schon mal am arbeitsplatz belästigt.
die dunkelziffer dürfte noch um einiges höher liegen, denn die wenigsten melden es oder sprechen darüber.
•
wo fängt denn sexuelle belästigung an? 
eine ungewollte umarmung oder berührung sind auf jeden fall nicht in ordnung.
•
wir zeigen euch in unserem stronger-frauenprogramm, wie ihr damit umgeht und was ihr aktiv dagegen tun könnt.
wir nutzen techniken, die speziell auf die bedürfnisse von frauen zugeschnitten sind und leicht umzusetzen sind.
bei uns kann man sich als frau wohlfühlen und sich unter gleichgesinnten austauschen. 
ab donnerstag, 22.11.2018 von 19-20uhr.

text:
vulnerability - many of us struggle with being vulnerable.  it scares us.  we feel raw, exposed, and defenseless.  i am reading brené brown’s new book, “dare to lead” - i am loving it!  she has such great insights, including vulnerability.  today i will be sharing some of her powerful quotes.

along with vulnerability, many of us struggle with feelings - especially the ones we have decided are not necessarily “good feelings” - you know them - “sad”, angry”, “scary”, “frightened” just to make a few... yet to feel these feelings allow us to truly experience “joy”, “happiness”, “contentment”.... feelings and vulnerability are not weaknesses, they are strengths 💜

| #thisisnotconsent 🌈💪🏻🧝🏼‍♀️
per chi non lo sapesse, lo scorso 6 novembre in irlanda, più precisamente in un tribunale di corck un ventisettenne è stato scagionato dall’accusa di violenza sessuale contro una diciassettenne, perché secondo il giudice la minorenne portava biancheria “troppo sexy”. una affermazione che da il voltastomaco. il vestiario non implica un qualsiasi consenso da parte di chi lo indossa. no significa no. accusare una ragazzina di “essersela cercata” per aver indossato un perizoma non è nemmeno da prendere in considerazione. ogniuno deve essere trattato con rispetto, a prescindere da cosa indossa. una minigonna o una maglia scollata non vuol dire “sono facile” “ ti consento di..” .questo non è altro che pura ignoranza e deve essere punita.

text:
⚠️ trigger warning, abuse discussed 💗
.
attention victims of abuse, repeat after me: .
“it’s not my fault.”
.
i know that intellectually you know that obviously it’s not your fault. but do you really feel like it? but it took me until my last therapy session yesterday, to really start processing that it’s not my fault. as my shrink said: “it’s not your fault, it’s all those men who abused you who are friggin psychopaths.” (i have the best shrink 😍)
.
regardless of what patriarchy tells us, no matter what the abuser made you believe, regardless of what you think & feel, no matter how guilty you feel, it’s not your fault.
you did not bring this upon you. doesn’t matter what you were wearing, how drunk you were, how much love you needed, if you fought back or not, if you feel like you let yourself get drugged, what they told you, how they manipulated you.... you did not bring this upon yourself. it’s not your fault.
i feel like robin william in good will hunting when he’s talking to matt damon 😋.
.
it’s not your fault. it’s not your fault. it’s not your fault. it’s not your fault. .
your trauma is real and it is legit even if you’ve never talked about it anyone. .
i used to sleep around a lot in my twenties, and i felt like a slut and therefore assumed that i had brought it upon myself. it’s insane to think how many times i’ve been abused, physically or emotionally, and to think i have felt like it was my fault for so long.
it’s not. it’s not my fault. it’s not your fault. i didn’t deserve this and neither do you. 
and men too, if you’re a man and you’re a victim of abuse, your trauma is as valid and legit as ours and it’s definitely not your fault either.💗
.
the good news it’s that it’s possible to reconstruct ourselves and get our self-esteem, value and dignity back.
i just thought it was important to share.
.
you are so loved 💗 you matter 💗 you belong 💗 you are worth it. .
.
.
.
.
#metoo #traumasurvivor #itsnotyourfault #abuse #nomeansno #victimshaming #victimofabuse #healfromtrauma #healtrauma #ptsd #youareloved #youarebeautiful #youareworthit #youmatter #healwithlove

i used to sleep around a lot in my twenties, and i felt like a slut and therefore assumed that i had brought it upon myself. it’s insane to think how many times i’ve been abused, physically or emotionally, and to think i have felt like it was my fault for so long.
it’s not. it’s not my fault. it’s not your fault. i didn’t deserve this and neither do you. 
and men too, if you’re a man and you’re a victim of abuse, your trauma is as valid and legit as ours and it’s definitely not your fault either.💗
.
the good news it’s that it’s possible to reconstruct ourselves and get our self-esteem, value and dignity back.
i just thought it was important to share.
.
you are so loved 💗 you matter 💗 you belong 💗 you are worth it. .
.
.
.
.

text:
"heyy, you know, she wore 'salwar kameez' in our annual day. so old fashioned she is."
we usually judge people this way, right? we usually measure the level of their fashion on the basis of clothes they wear. we think that fashion is always about short-tops and hot-pants but heyy, please don't think that way. fashion isn't always about clothes but sometimes it's about how comfortable we are in them. yes it is! if you're feeling comfortable in short-tops, you're fashionable. if you're comfortable in hot-pants, you are fashionable. if you're comfortable in salwar-kameez, you're fashionable. if you're comfortable in hijaab, you're fashionable. let them judge. choose your comfort, choose your fashion.
.
.
©anjali @uncaged_emotions_

pic credits: nezha

text:
jnicsr foundation is pleased to announce the official launch of jnicsr times magazine vol.3 issue. 11. the much awaited magazine, was developed in cooperation with team jnicsr. we offer rich and relevant content that reflects the corporate social responsibility, personality and vivacity. jnicsr times will be on the web at www.jnicsrtimes.com. the magazine was unveiled in new delhi this morning, with full team and family of jnicsr foundation.

this time jnicsr times is  featuring a cover story on “a csr can help reduce the great gender divide: #me too movement is a great step in the history of women empowerment ” and introducing jnicsr following articles:

1.  promotion of education, special education and vocational skills.

the visual and editorial quality of jnicsr times is top-notch and its pages are inspired by the values and interests of corporate social responsibility. the magazine’s style is elegant and sparkling, simple and contemporary, and creates an inviting world that has something for underprivileged and poor in every area of their lives. readers will find special sections that include cover story, article and current updates of csr. “jnicsr foundation is very proud to be associated with jnicsr times, one of the most admired and respected csr magazine.

after hours and days of work, we can finally unveil our vol.3 issue. 11! what a delight! working on the vol.3 issue. 11 was a highly enriching experience for us and we want to thank the fabulous team at jnicsr times for their collaboration and support in this magnificent adventure.

text:
"when we say the future belongs to young people, who are these young people? the ones who are sneaked out of their countries for sex trade? the ones who are denied basic education? the ones who languish in poverty and hopelessness? who are these young people we keep talking about?" writes vigilance atieno on her latest blog post.

just like you, vigilance odoyo believes in the potential and power of youth, but she dares to ask the questions that have been lingering on our minds for a while now. 
according to asec, the countries with the highest rates of modern slavery in sub-saharan africa are central african republic, democratic republic of the congo, somalia, south sudan, sudan and mauritania. “governments wake up, protect and serve your citizens!” pleads @vigilance_odoyo .

read vigilance's article for a clearer picture of what is happening outside your windows, much much closer than you can possibly imagine. (link in bio) ———————————————————————

text:
>>> une semaine / une personnalite <<< en ce 17 novembre nous souhaitions vous présenter françoise héritier. françoise héritier nous a quitté il y a an, le 15 novembre 2017, succombant à une maladie rare auto-immune contre laquelle elle se battait depuis l’âge de 50 ans.
françoise héritier était une anthropologue et ethnologue notoire, héritière de claude lévi-strauss selon ses propres mots.
directrice d’étude à l’ehess (écoles des hautes études en sciences sociales), elle a succédé à claude lévi-strauss au collège de france, inaugurant les « études comparée des sociétés africaines ».
françoise héritier est notamment célèbre et reconnue dans le milieu universitaire pour ses écrits tels que « masculin / féminin », publié en 1996. elle y expose notamment sa thèse dite de la « valence différentielle des sexes ». cette thèse affirme que les différences que l’on peut retrouver, dans toute société, entre les hommes et les femmes, mais également la supériorité de l’homme sur la femme, n’a pas de fondement naturel et biologique. cette différence est alors le résultat d’une construction sociale et culturelle. cette thèse a servi d’argument d’autorité majeur pour le mouvement féministe.
en effet, puisqu’il s’agit de la femme qui porte l’enfant et qui dispose de ce « pouvoir », l’homme a essayé d’asseoir sa domination sur d’autres sphères car s’est senti privé de ce pouvoir de procréation détenu de manière monopolistique par le sexe féminin. la valence différentielle des sexes dispose donc que cette construction sociale qui suppose une infériorité des femmes, est le résultat de représentations que l’on s’est formées autour de caractéristiques naturelles et biologiques. 
françoise héritier dans les derniers moments de sa vie, s’était également engagée dans la défense de l’homoparentalité, la mise en garde et la réflexion quant au risque de marchandisation du corps des femmes, notamment pauvres, avec la gpa, sans pour autant prendre réellement partie, et avait enfin soutenu le mouvement de libération de la parole des femmes quant à leurs agressions sexuelles avec le #metoo.
nous lui rendons donc aujourd’hui hommage et soutenons son nom pour représenter la promotion 2022.

text: i can hardly leave my house without getting catcalled. i’m serious. sometimes on days when i don’t have anywhere to be, i stay home just to avoid conflict. i’ve had people tell me i should be flattered by the attention. that i’m lucky to be *this* beautiful. but it’s not complimentary. being harassed daily is not a badge of honor. and i know the actual reason has little to do with my appearance: it’s because the objectification of women of color has been normalized by the white patriarchy. so normalized, in fact, that when they do find us appealing (*gasp*), they have to justify it by categorically segregating us, then marginalize us further by using descriptors and qualifiers that are rooted in racism. think about the use of the word “exotic” to describe a woman’s appearance. by definition, that word means foreign. alien. strange. unusual. think about the phrase “pretty for a ______ girl.” when’s the last time you can remember that blank being filled in by the word “white”? we are taught that non-white beauty is not normal. and this is one of the reasons why wocs are abused and assaulted as at such higher rates than white women. my freshman year of college, i met a white man who wanted to sleep with a woman of every race by the end of the academic year. he had an actual list in his wallet. and he told me- without shame or hesitation- that he wanted to hook up with me so he could check off two races at once. then he groped me without my consent. then he called me a prude when i wouldn’t “go further” than that. he told me that no one would want to be with me because i was so uptight, and that my beauty was going to waste since i wasn’t sexually engaging with anyone. this is just one of i-don’t-even-know-how-many experiences i’ve had in my life. and i know that i am just one of countless woc who have experienced things like this. stop othering non-white beauty. it’s not a compliment. it’s not flattering. it’s gross. and it’s dangerous. #notyourbaby #metoo #endrapeculture #survivor #believesurvivors #woc #intersectionalfeminism
name: Mel Hanley | Survivor Advocate

text:
‘gender equality in the photography industry. from fashion to reportage’ 👉 a conversation with @alessiaglaviano , photojournalist @anastasiatl , photographer @relbw , curator and filmmaker @goliverio_ and photoeditor, curator, cultural producer and educator @monica.allende ✨ join the talk today at @base_milano at 6pm 👉 free entrance, you’re all invited!
👉 at present, the world is still built upon mechanisms shaped around a male perspective and power structures are predominantly dominated by men. women have been fighting for generations for equal human, political and social rights and yet there are still plenty of difficulties and struggles on a daily basis. it is true, however, that the revolution started by the new media and the fast circulation of news and ideas made them even stronger and movements like black lives matter or tarana burke’s #metoo were capable of bringing them together in a common project. on their part, female artists and photographers voice such reality addressing topics but, most of all, providing a direct female perspective. and if photography is also a tool for change and a mirror of the world we live in, the picture showing gender inequality in photography reveals significant shortcomings.
read the programme about all the talks on vogue.it 💬

text:
#metoo
i will share about something i hear or get contacted a lot about and something i have experienced.it is subject of #sexualabuse and it's relation to outfit. i don't want to write a lot but what i want all the girls out there understand is that it is never your fault when you are harrassed or what is worse raped. no matter what you dress like there is a certain type of men which is a majority type ( in my humble opinion) who will abuse you. just learn to respond. it is something we are never taught and when we speak up we get the blame. #blamingvictim is very common practice in all countries around the world. never be afraid to talk about it and never feel you are to blame. you are innocent it is them who did this to you. don't feel you are filthy and undeserving of love. you are beautiful, wonderful creature who had to experience terrible things but dont let this stop you from living life to its fullest. dont change and hide yourself. do not ruin your life and again never take the blame. lastly, always always speak up, fight back. you are the hero who will save you. no one else will. 
#girlpower

text:
i attended the tata literature fest today and i'm as happy as one can be. words make me feel loved and hugged and enough all at the same time. 
i heard strong women like kalki koechlin (taking a moment to be a fan girl because i got her autograph!), harnidh kaur and various others speak about the #metoo movement. the session with karan thapar and sagarika ghose was amazing and the one where shobhaa de conversed with upamaniyu chatterjee only made the day better. 
while i was sitting there on the pink seat as a part of the audience, i almost imagined how wonderful would it be to finally become a great author.
someday i hope i step into the tata theatre, walk right inside, glance at the pink seats and keep walking till i reach the stage where i take the mic and greet the people there as an author.
i know it's a big dream. a very big one.
but i have a tiny and silly theory in life.
if we settle for less and don't dream big, we might not lose anything but we also stop the magic that could be meant for us.
when we do dream big, we have a lot to lose because dreaming is a hard work, my friend. however, this way we are at least aiming for the moon. and a wise man has already told us what happens when we aim for the moon. yes, we land between the stars.
so, this is me, dreaming big and being crazy enough to actually think they will come true.
someday i'll come for the tata literature festival as an author. call me crazy, but i actually do think this will happen.
the universe and i have a strong connection. i ask for something and it opens up ways for me.
let me leave you with a secret.
don't ever ask the universe for less than you want because it grants only what we ask.
be courageous and ask it to make all your 'oh my god, this is insane' dreams true, and it will.
it always will.
that's my promise :)
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
ah so i’m actually really nervous to post this because i still have that part inside of me that i battle with that says “no one cares. no one can love this part of you” but that’s exactly why i need to share this with you. swipe right for the full video sequence. 
today i’m talking about ptsd and how your intuition can help you through it (like it helps me through mine! 🙋🏼‍♀️). when we keep things bottled up inside of us 🤐because of shame or fear we block our throat chakra🙅🏼‍♀️
if you see your throat chakra as a vent, when it gets blocked it creates a ton of stress and build up in the rest of the body until something explodes.🤯 this reek havoc on our mental and physical health😖
you intuiton will guide you to the right people for you to talk to. 👫it can guide you to the right remedies to help get you back into alignment. it can be your best friend even when you feel scared, alone and like curling up into a ball by yourself 🤗
i’m here to tell you that you are not alone, love. i am here for you. i am going through challenges right along with you. and because of my intuition, i’ve been able to come so far. even at my weakest moments now, i feel so much better than i felt before💪🏻 even though those painful parts may not seem lovable, they are and your intuition can help you see that 👁 i learned how to use the traumas that i endured as a kid to heighten my intuitive abilities. you can do the same. send me a dm and we can talk about working together and if that’s right for you. so much love, danielle just reach for help because when you don’t, they win. #stopthesilence #metoo
